WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:01.110 --> 00:00:03.214
ROB KENNER: Welcome everybody.

00:00:03.214 --> 00:00:04.130
My name is Rob Kenner.

00:00:04.130 --> 00:00:06.100
I'm a senior editor
at Complex Media.

00:00:06.100 --> 00:00:09.420
And I'm glad that all of
you could join us here

00:00:09.420 --> 00:00:13.000
in the flesh and
digitally, virtually around

00:00:13.000 --> 00:00:15.930
the Google diaspora.

00:00:15.930 --> 00:00:19.050
And I'm joined by Mr. Marc Ecko.

00:00:19.050 --> 00:00:19.800
Round of applause.

00:00:23.980 --> 00:00:27.740
MARC ECKO: Then they add
like the "roar" track.

00:00:27.740 --> 00:00:29.120
You'll just cut that in.

00:00:29.120 --> 00:00:31.112
It'll be like [ROAR].

00:00:31.112 --> 00:00:33.070
ROB KENNER: Or the Norman
Lear canned laughter.

00:00:33.070 --> 00:00:35.740
MARC ECKO: Right, right.

00:00:35.740 --> 00:00:38.615
With the delayed hand clap.

00:00:38.615 --> 00:00:40.490
ROB KENNER: We're counting
on the laugh lines

00:00:40.490 --> 00:00:42.060
to go over really big today.

00:00:42.060 --> 00:00:43.540
So please participate.

00:00:43.540 --> 00:00:46.760
MARC ECKO: Follow the
applaud signs if you will.

00:00:46.760 --> 00:00:49.320
ROB KENNER: So you
may know Marc Ecko

00:00:49.320 --> 00:00:54.200
as the designer of the
rhinoceros t-shirts

00:00:54.200 --> 00:00:57.950
and as a fly MC.

00:00:57.950 --> 00:01:00.245
There's a lot of different
items on his resume.

00:01:00.245 --> 00:01:06.270
But today he's here in
the guise of an author.

00:01:06.270 --> 00:01:10.000
His book "Unlabel, Selling
You Without Selling Out"

00:01:10.000 --> 00:01:13.599
is, as he describes
it, the textbook you

00:01:13.599 --> 00:01:15.140
wish you had when
you were in school.

00:01:15.140 --> 00:01:16.040
MARC ECKO: Yes.

00:01:16.040 --> 00:01:17.282
Yes.

00:01:17.282 --> 00:01:19.100
ROB KENNER: Now it's
called "Unlabel."

00:01:19.100 --> 00:01:20.240
MARC ECKO: Yes.

00:01:20.240 --> 00:01:25.560
ROB KENNER: Tell me what labels
were put on you that you undid.

00:01:25.560 --> 00:01:29.250
MARC ECKO: Well,
what I try to do

00:01:29.250 --> 00:01:33.030
with the book was build
a kind of a business book

00:01:33.030 --> 00:01:34.820
for the creative class.

00:01:34.820 --> 00:01:39.140
And in an age where we
have all these efficiencies

00:01:39.140 --> 00:01:43.970
of self-broadcasting
because of digital media,

00:01:43.970 --> 00:01:46.330
I wanted to write
a book that had

00:01:46.330 --> 00:01:48.180
a subtext about
personal branding,

00:01:48.180 --> 00:01:52.220
but without being this
patronizing, goopy, personal

00:01:52.220 --> 00:01:55.850
branding book, which those
books tend to be like.

00:01:55.850 --> 00:01:58.170
So the spirit of
the name "Unlabel"

00:01:58.170 --> 00:01:59.810
was-- it had a few meanings.

00:01:59.810 --> 00:02:03.400
One, the brand that I launched
was called Ecko Unlimited,

00:02:03.400 --> 00:02:08.440
so it's playing up on the U-N
like the "un" from "unlimited."

00:02:08.440 --> 00:02:11.770
And secondly, I was playing
up on this notion of the fact

00:02:11.770 --> 00:02:15.610
that we-- it's just
human nature-- people

00:02:15.610 --> 00:02:16.940
project labels onto us.

00:02:16.940 --> 00:02:19.960
They want to organize us in
the world like a product,

00:02:19.960 --> 00:02:23.080
if we like it or not,
if we know it or not,

00:02:23.080 --> 00:02:26.110
sometimes with good intent
or with decent intent

00:02:26.110 --> 00:02:28.240
to make people's
lives more efficient,

00:02:28.240 --> 00:02:31.290
sometimes with kind
of not so good intent.

00:02:31.290 --> 00:02:36.090
So in a world where people
are so easily spewing

00:02:36.090 --> 00:02:39.380
out their persona,
their brand, I

00:02:39.380 --> 00:02:41.270
was trying to make
the reader flatfooted

00:02:41.270 --> 00:02:45.160
and have kind of an analog
conversation about what

00:02:45.160 --> 00:02:50.420
it means to build a personal
brand, what it means to live up

00:02:50.420 --> 00:02:53.030
to that brand, the brand
that you perceive-- which

00:02:53.030 --> 00:02:55.480
is the label, like
the exterior veneer,

00:02:55.480 --> 00:02:59.134
the flourishes, the
outside packaging.

00:02:59.134 --> 00:03:01.300
And the label you have to
put to bed at night, which

00:03:01.300 --> 00:03:03.210
is the one that's
guts to the skin.

00:03:03.210 --> 00:03:06.130
So how do you discern
and distinguish

00:03:06.130 --> 00:03:10.350
between your inside brand, your
inside label and your exterior

00:03:10.350 --> 00:03:10.910
one?

00:03:10.910 --> 00:03:16.650
And how do you not parrot,
either within intent

00:03:16.650 --> 00:03:19.770
or with poor intent
or misguided intent

00:03:19.770 --> 00:03:23.160
to the perceived skin
to the world brand.

00:03:23.160 --> 00:03:28.700
So the book, in a
digital age, tries

00:03:28.700 --> 00:03:32.930
to have a not too serious
conversation but something that

00:03:32.930 --> 00:03:36.590
helps people understand
my philosophy on branding

00:03:36.590 --> 00:03:40.460
and maybe how that might be
helpful to their personal

00:03:40.460 --> 00:03:44.940
brand, if it's their personal
singular brand or their group

00:03:44.940 --> 00:03:47.680
collective "we" company brand.

00:03:47.680 --> 00:03:50.090
ROB KENNER: Now what I
love about the book is

00:03:50.090 --> 00:03:53.740
it's not like a typical
sort of Trump book,

00:03:53.740 --> 00:03:56.550
where it's all about
the Ws and the Ls

00:03:56.550 --> 00:03:58.010
kind of get airbrushed out.

00:03:58.010 --> 00:04:00.422
MARC ECKO: Right.

00:04:00.422 --> 00:04:04.120
ROB KENNER: To be clear, you did
grow an air brushing business

00:04:04.120 --> 00:04:07.230
from your parents garage into
a company with $1 billion

00:04:07.230 --> 00:04:08.130
in revenue.

00:04:08.130 --> 00:04:08.680
MARC ECKO: That's right.

00:04:08.680 --> 00:04:10.388
ROB KENNER: And you
founded Complex Media

00:04:10.388 --> 00:04:11.980
which is killing
the game right now.

00:04:11.980 --> 00:04:12.940
MARC ECKO: Yup.

00:04:12.940 --> 00:04:15.520
ROB KENNER: But let's
talk about the Ls,

00:04:15.520 --> 00:04:18.430
because those are
teachable moments.

00:04:18.430 --> 00:04:21.709
MARC ECKO: I think
this book is designed

00:04:21.709 --> 00:04:28.000
not to be what a lot of
those very 90s-style, Type

00:04:28.000 --> 00:04:30.101
A personality business
books, like the guy

00:04:30.101 --> 00:04:32.350
parachutes out of the plane
like Richard Branson-style

00:04:32.350 --> 00:04:34.360
and doesn't fail.

00:04:34.360 --> 00:04:36.705
I think this book
is more of-- instead

00:04:36.705 --> 00:04:38.080
of being a book
on greatest hits,

00:04:38.080 --> 00:04:40.310
it's more of a book
on my greatest misses.

00:04:40.310 --> 00:04:48.700
And I'm someone who really likes
to be honest and even painfully

00:04:48.700 --> 00:04:55.230
at times masochistically
honest about my idiosyncrasies,

00:04:55.230 --> 00:05:00.810
my failures, just because it's--
I don't believe how failures

00:05:00.810 --> 00:05:04.290
are taught to be in school, that
you should be ashamed of them.

00:05:04.290 --> 00:05:07.470
Like K through 12, the sentence
we all go through that K

00:05:07.470 --> 00:05:09.620
through 12 sentence
that we all get,

00:05:09.620 --> 00:05:13.210
no matter the state puts
us through, public, private

00:05:13.210 --> 00:05:17.240
or otherwise, we're taught
that failure something

00:05:17.240 --> 00:05:19.170
to be embarrassed by.

00:05:19.170 --> 00:05:22.225
It's something you ridicule,
something to be ashamed by.

00:05:22.225 --> 00:05:25.230
And it's just funny
how in business

00:05:25.230 --> 00:05:28.516
that success never really
quite looks like an A,

00:05:28.516 --> 00:05:30.780
and failure never
quite looks like an F.

00:05:30.780 --> 00:05:34.240
And how much value there is
in the learnings of failure.

00:05:34.240 --> 00:05:38.000
So I try to have a really honest
conversation about failure,

00:05:38.000 --> 00:05:42.080
and put it out there in a
way that maybe people have

00:05:42.080 --> 00:05:45.030
perceived me as this guy
that's built this big business

00:05:45.030 --> 00:05:48.930
and has collected all
this stuff-- right?

00:05:48.930 --> 00:05:51.640
The trappings of success.

00:05:51.640 --> 00:05:54.150
But I didn't make the
book about gushing around

00:05:54.150 --> 00:05:56.530
about the stuff I collected.

00:05:56.530 --> 00:05:58.980
Like the real value and the
real wealth that I talk about

00:05:58.980 --> 00:06:00.820
in the book, the
wealth that matters,

00:06:00.820 --> 00:06:04.080
can't really be
counted like money.

00:06:04.080 --> 00:06:05.880
And it's funny how the
wealth that matters

00:06:05.880 --> 00:06:08.156
can be distributed
differently as well.

00:06:08.156 --> 00:06:09.880
ROB KENNER: Definitely.

00:06:09.880 --> 00:06:12.085
There is a part
in the book where

00:06:12.085 --> 00:06:14.330
you talk about
getting into denim,

00:06:14.330 --> 00:06:19.040
and your way of feeling
your way through that.

00:06:19.040 --> 00:06:21.602
And I thought that was
an instructive anecdote.

00:06:21.602 --> 00:06:23.560
Is there a way you could
boil that down for me?

00:06:23.560 --> 00:06:26.000
MARC ECKO: Was that the
part in the book where

00:06:26.000 --> 00:06:28.300
I meet with Wu, the
dentist supplier?

00:06:28.300 --> 00:06:29.130
I can't remember.

00:06:29.130 --> 00:06:30.080
ROB KENNER: Yeah.

00:06:30.080 --> 00:06:31.050
And the rivets.

00:06:31.050 --> 00:06:35.700
MARC ECKO: Oh, right right,
Look, today the world

00:06:35.700 --> 00:06:42.530
we live in, young designers
and young product makers today,

00:06:42.530 --> 00:06:45.619
the world's a much
different world.

00:06:45.619 --> 00:06:47.910
There's this thing, you guys
probably have heard of it,

00:06:47.910 --> 00:06:50.000
it's called Google.

00:06:50.000 --> 00:06:54.830
So if you ask it, you can
find out a lot of shit.

00:06:54.830 --> 00:06:56.947
Back when I was coming
up, like the Google

00:06:56.947 --> 00:06:59.030
was like looking at the
inside label of whatever I

00:06:59.030 --> 00:07:00.600
was wearing.

00:07:00.600 --> 00:07:04.800
I'd look at the inside of
my Gap hoodie or whatever,

00:07:04.800 --> 00:07:07.190
and it was like
"Made in Hong Kong."

00:07:07.190 --> 00:07:08.550
Like, where is Hong Kong?

00:07:08.550 --> 00:07:10.670
Is that by India?

00:07:10.670 --> 00:07:14.200
Much of my education was so so.

00:07:14.200 --> 00:07:16.070
But I literally
just packed a bag

00:07:16.070 --> 00:07:17.920
and found myself over there.

00:07:17.920 --> 00:07:21.030
But was only after
I attempted to try

00:07:21.030 --> 00:07:23.257
to figure it all
out in the States.

00:07:23.257 --> 00:07:25.090
And that's the anecdote
you're asking about,

00:07:25.090 --> 00:07:31.630
where I had found a denim
maker-- I forget where they

00:07:31.630 --> 00:07:36.150
were in the South
somewhere-- and they

00:07:36.150 --> 00:07:41.360
put like all the rivets and
shanks on in the wrong manner.

00:07:41.360 --> 00:07:42.360
And they all popped off.

00:07:42.360 --> 00:07:44.250
So I remember shipping
them months late,

00:07:44.250 --> 00:07:47.260
and then having-- after we
got the first return-- having

00:07:47.260 --> 00:07:51.830
to manually fix that stuff
ourselves in our warehouses.

00:07:51.830 --> 00:07:56.459
But there are a lot of
anecdotes like that,

00:07:56.459 --> 00:07:58.125
stuff that you don't
really contemplate,

00:07:58.125 --> 00:08:00.640
like the consequences
of the things you make

00:08:00.640 --> 00:08:05.350
and the complexities of them,
and how they affect your--

00:08:05.350 --> 00:08:09.390
you don't anticipate that
they're going to go wrong.

00:08:09.390 --> 00:08:10.287
But they do.

00:08:10.287 --> 00:08:11.120
ROB KENNER: They do.

00:08:11.120 --> 00:08:12.630
MARC ECKO: Yup, they do.

00:08:12.630 --> 00:08:14.910
ROB KENNER: But what I
love about your candor

00:08:14.910 --> 00:08:16.950
in telling these
stories, is it gets back

00:08:16.950 --> 00:08:19.900
to this idea of authenticity,
keeping it real,

00:08:19.900 --> 00:08:23.770
in hop hop lingo.

00:08:23.770 --> 00:08:27.090
You actually break down
the formula of authenticity

00:08:27.090 --> 00:08:30.560
in the book, which is kind
of a closely guarded secret.

00:08:30.560 --> 00:08:32.409
I mentioned that Malcolm
Gladwell gave you

00:08:32.409 --> 00:08:35.295
props for attempting to
break down authenticity.

00:08:38.210 --> 00:08:40.780
It's sort of akin to
the Google algorithm.

00:08:40.780 --> 00:08:44.179
How do you penetrate the
mystery of authenticity.

00:08:44.179 --> 00:08:46.420
MARC ECKO: I think it
was a little bit what

00:08:46.420 --> 00:08:48.460
a part of the book is
about, and the book

00:08:48.460 --> 00:08:51.790
being framed like a
textbook, was a little bit

00:08:51.790 --> 00:08:58.500
taking the piss out of these
kind of prescriptive methods

00:08:58.500 --> 00:09:02.570
of arriving at a best practice,
as if you could really

00:09:02.570 --> 00:09:05.680
prescribe an for authenticity.

00:09:05.680 --> 00:09:08.450
It's like we all bought
into that whole e equals

00:09:08.450 --> 00:09:12.320
mc squared thing, but I
mean, have we vetted it.

00:09:12.320 --> 00:09:12.820
Really?

00:09:12.820 --> 00:09:14.278
Like we all just
agree, because you

00:09:14.278 --> 00:09:16.370
see the guy with the crazy hair.

00:09:16.370 --> 00:09:18.760
And we were all told "genius."

00:09:18.760 --> 00:09:20.260
And I mean yeah,
I'm not trying to--

00:09:20.260 --> 00:09:21.730
ROB KENNER: Well, guys with
crazy hair are always geniuses.

00:09:21.730 --> 00:09:24.070
MARC ECKO: Right, I mean,
I know this from Rob.

00:09:24.070 --> 00:09:28.120
So we all know this, right?

00:09:28.120 --> 00:09:35.110
But to your point, hop hop
and coming up in the '80s

00:09:35.110 --> 00:09:37.510
when hip hop was this thing
you had to go find it.

00:09:37.510 --> 00:09:39.720
It didn't find you in the
way that it kind of is so

00:09:39.720 --> 00:09:43.520
woven into popular culture and
consumer products and our media

00:09:43.520 --> 00:09:47.710
narratives and our language.

00:09:47.710 --> 00:09:51.330
So there was in its kind
of prepubescent phase,

00:09:51.330 --> 00:09:53.490
hip hop had this
awkwardness about it,

00:09:53.490 --> 00:09:57.470
about its comfort or lack of
comfort around commercializing

00:09:57.470 --> 00:10:00.360
itself, around quote
"crossing over."

00:10:00.360 --> 00:10:02.200
So there was a lot
of tension coming up

00:10:02.200 --> 00:10:04.840
in the '80s around
"keeping it real"

00:10:04.840 --> 00:10:07.490
and this notion of
what's real, what's not,

00:10:07.490 --> 00:10:09.950
what's authentic, what's not.

00:10:09.950 --> 00:10:12.340
And there were all kinds
of layers of subtext there

00:10:12.340 --> 00:10:16.860
that, depending on who you
ask, had different meanings.

00:10:16.860 --> 00:10:18.430
But that was certainly
something that

00:10:18.430 --> 00:10:22.010
was one of the things
that kind of dogged hip

00:10:22.010 --> 00:10:26.250
hop in its kind of early
prepubescent years.

00:10:26.250 --> 00:10:31.740
Even to this day, real hard
core hip hop enthusiasts

00:10:31.740 --> 00:10:34.870
will take a default,
almost cynical view

00:10:34.870 --> 00:10:37.430
on anything that
tries to commercialize

00:10:37.430 --> 00:10:39.740
in a certain way, where the
monetization strategy is

00:10:39.740 --> 00:10:41.600
kind of overt.

00:10:41.600 --> 00:10:45.740
Less today, but certainly
when I was coming up.

00:10:45.740 --> 00:10:50.687
So that was a theme in
the subtext of my story

00:10:50.687 --> 00:10:51.770
and is a part of the book.

00:10:51.770 --> 00:10:56.900
that kind of always having an
answer to quote "gatekeepers,"

00:10:56.900 --> 00:11:00.870
who would challenge what
was authentic or not.

00:11:00.870 --> 00:11:05.010
So not being kind of blue blood
pedigree fashion designer,

00:11:05.010 --> 00:11:07.260
you can imagine what it was
like to get into the CFDA.

00:11:07.260 --> 00:11:08.676
And I talk about
that in the book.

00:11:08.676 --> 00:11:10.810
The Council of Fashion
Designers of America.

00:11:10.810 --> 00:11:14.520
And some of those
kind of cultural I'll

00:11:14.520 --> 00:11:17.750
use the word-- prejudices
that that ecosystem has

00:11:17.750 --> 00:11:22.422
as gatekeepers around street
wear and urban fashion design.

00:11:22.422 --> 00:11:24.130
MARC ECKO: Just the
word urban in itself.

00:11:24.130 --> 00:11:26.004
ROB KENNER: Right, its
like so loaded, right?

00:11:26.004 --> 00:11:28.080
So that's not real
fashion design.

00:11:28.080 --> 00:11:29.110
It's not authentic.

00:11:29.110 --> 00:11:32.660
And then all the way down to
like coming up in my Rutgers

00:11:32.660 --> 00:11:38.450
college age is like, look,
white Jewish kid, into hip hop,

00:11:38.450 --> 00:11:41.410
going to Rutgers, it was nothing
like Lakewood in that Lakewood

00:11:41.410 --> 00:11:44.990
was kind of this
microcosm, and then

00:11:44.990 --> 00:11:48.200
Rutgers is much more
of a macrochosm of how

00:11:48.200 --> 00:11:52.860
people really kind of
socially accepted people

00:11:52.860 --> 00:11:56.680
cross kind of racial
lines and boundaries.

00:11:56.680 --> 00:12:01.550
So coming up in the early
'90s, I graduated high school

00:12:01.550 --> 00:12:04.265
in 1990-- so going
off to Rutgers,

00:12:04.265 --> 00:12:06.140
there were definitely
people that looked down

00:12:06.140 --> 00:12:07.880
their nose-- black and
white and otherwise.

00:12:07.880 --> 00:12:09.630
Right there were kind
of like a little bit

00:12:09.630 --> 00:12:12.456
skeptical, like who's this
kid, coming up in this space,

00:12:12.456 --> 00:12:14.330
airbrushing t-shirts,
talking about graffiti.

00:12:14.330 --> 00:12:16.820
That's not really
graffiti, That's airbrush.

00:12:16.820 --> 00:12:18.070
That's not authentic.

00:12:18.070 --> 00:12:20.470
So what the book
attempts to do is

00:12:20.470 --> 00:12:24.430
take what the best practices
of authenticity are.

00:12:24.430 --> 00:12:27.940
And I assign this formula--
it's kind of convoluted.

00:12:27.940 --> 00:12:29.130
It's a little clunky.

00:12:29.130 --> 00:12:32.860
But I think it frames the
real important components

00:12:32.860 --> 00:12:35.030
to creating an
authentic expression,

00:12:35.030 --> 00:12:40.260
an authentic interaction,
communication,

00:12:40.260 --> 00:12:42.870
and the components
just on a high level.

00:12:42.870 --> 00:12:46.040
There is the notion
of the unique voice,

00:12:46.040 --> 00:12:49.890
the role of selfishness,
one's creative selfishness

00:12:49.890 --> 00:12:55.260
and intent, which is often
when we get all kumbaya

00:12:55.260 --> 00:12:57.150
and want to design
by committee, we

00:12:57.150 --> 00:12:58.800
lose that selfish perspective.

00:13:01.440 --> 00:13:06.590
Truthfulness, being
defined by your ability

00:13:06.590 --> 00:13:08.210
to do more than you say.

00:13:08.210 --> 00:13:11.260
Because a lot culturally,
we're just busy talking.

00:13:11.260 --> 00:13:15.460
And in this era of
social media, we almost

00:13:15.460 --> 00:13:18.359
think because we
said it, we did it.

