00:42:48.990 --> 00:42:51.199
AUDIENCE: How did you
originally get backing behind--

00:42:51.199 --> 00:42:52.406
MARC ECKO: Financial backing?

00:42:52.406 --> 00:42:53.760
AUDIENCE: Yeah.

00:42:53.760 --> 00:42:57.140
MARC ECKO: I talk about it in
the book, which again speaks

00:42:57.140 --> 00:42:59.400
to the whole subtext
of perception, reality,

00:42:59.400 --> 00:43:04.970
because my perception was that
I'd been servicing and creating

00:43:04.970 --> 00:43:09.040
relationships with a lot
of celebrities at the time.

00:43:09.040 --> 00:43:11.080
And I presumed like
that celebrity there,

00:43:11.080 --> 00:43:16.610
X, like in this one instance-- I
don't know if you guys remember

00:43:16.610 --> 00:43:18.800
a group called Bell
Biv Devoe They're

00:43:18.800 --> 00:43:20.222
derivative from New Edition.

00:43:20.222 --> 00:43:21.930
There's a guy named
Michael Bivins, who's

00:43:21.930 --> 00:43:27.200
a real entrepreneurial cat,
very successful music producer.

00:43:27.200 --> 00:43:29.120
I actually was air
brushing for him

00:43:29.120 --> 00:43:31.890
and actually managed
to get my friend,

00:43:31.890 --> 00:43:33.750
Cale Brock, who's
mentioned in the book,

00:43:33.750 --> 00:43:36.830
signed to his record label
through that interaction.

00:43:36.830 --> 00:43:40.640
So I was going down the rabbit
hole of meeting music execs,

00:43:40.640 --> 00:43:42.700
and I just perceived--
I perceived, well,

00:43:42.700 --> 00:43:43.970
they have money.

00:43:43.970 --> 00:43:44.970
Look at the videos.

00:43:44.970 --> 00:43:46.340
Look at their influence.

00:43:46.340 --> 00:43:50.270
So I kept beating
pounding the drum.

00:43:50.270 --> 00:43:52.420
If it was Spike Lee,
soliciting Spike Lee,

00:43:52.420 --> 00:43:55.050
soliciting Biv, soliciting
a whole bunch of people

00:43:55.050 --> 00:43:57.690
that were just specifically
music industry.

00:43:57.690 --> 00:44:00.330
And what ended up
happening is one

00:44:00.330 --> 00:44:04.740
of those unsuspecting
characters, who didn't look

00:44:04.740 --> 00:44:08.320
and dress the part of
celebrity, became my partner,

00:44:08.320 --> 00:44:12.400
a guy named Seth Gerszberg, who
literally put the first $5,000

00:44:12.400 --> 00:44:13.450
into the company.

00:44:13.450 --> 00:44:18.290
And he kind of was my
commercialization beast.

00:44:18.290 --> 00:44:22.260
As a band goes, the composition
of the original company

00:44:22.260 --> 00:44:26.650
was my twin sister Marci, who
I talk about this in the book.

00:44:26.650 --> 00:44:27.980
She was like governance.

00:44:27.980 --> 00:44:31.690
Like she governed, kept the
boys from killing each other.

00:44:31.690 --> 00:44:34.350
And then there was
my partner Seth

00:44:34.350 --> 00:44:37.250
who was like the brute force
and the commercialization.

00:44:37.250 --> 00:44:39.650
And I was kind of like the
swag and the branded and kind

00:44:39.650 --> 00:44:42.960
of the emotional
part of the equation.

00:44:42.960 --> 00:44:47.390
But in tandem, we went out
there and kind of slowly

00:44:47.390 --> 00:44:50.350
from that initial
$5,000 investment,

00:44:50.350 --> 00:44:53.887
he managed to
coerce another group

00:44:53.887 --> 00:44:55.220
that he was doing business with.

00:44:55.220 --> 00:44:56.980
I talk about it in the book.

00:44:56.980 --> 00:44:58.830
And they were our
initial seed investors.

00:44:58.830 --> 00:45:02.470
And we eventually
bought them out.

00:45:02.470 --> 00:45:06.060
But it's not an easy--
getting funding,

00:45:06.060 --> 00:45:09.356
that's the trick
question, right?

00:45:09.356 --> 00:45:12.360
Or that's the $25,000 question.

00:45:12.360 --> 00:45:14.430
No pun intended, or
pun maybe intended.

00:45:14.430 --> 00:45:21.410
But there's no single one
way to do it obviously.

00:45:21.410 --> 00:45:23.370
And what's so fascinating
today with what's

00:45:23.370 --> 00:45:26.880
going on culturally with
like platforms like Indigogo

00:45:26.880 --> 00:45:30.970
or Kickstarter and a lower
path, a lower threshold,

00:45:30.970 --> 00:45:32.680
because of Google,
the fact you could

00:45:32.680 --> 00:45:34.680
kind of, from Google
or not, just directly

00:45:34.680 --> 00:45:38.520
go to Ali Baba or wherever and
source things domestically,

00:45:38.520 --> 00:45:39.600
oversees.

00:45:39.600 --> 00:45:42.310
The barrier to enter,
if you want to learn,

00:45:42.310 --> 00:45:45.180
if there's a wantedness,
is sufficiently lower.

00:45:45.180 --> 00:45:46.980
But it's that much noisier now.

00:45:46.980 --> 00:45:49.790
So that's why branding
is a really crucial part

00:45:49.790 --> 00:45:50.992
of the equation.

00:45:50.992 --> 00:45:51.700
AUDIENCE: Thanks.

00:45:51.700 --> 00:45:52.450
MARC ECKO: Cheers.

00:45:57.714 --> 00:45:58.880
AUDIENCE: My name's Kennedy.

00:45:58.880 --> 00:46:00.870
I appreciate you
coming out today.

00:46:00.870 --> 00:46:04.530
My question is did you ever
feel lost on this journey.

00:46:04.530 --> 00:46:06.880
I imagine that a lot
of entrepreneurs, they

00:46:06.880 --> 00:46:08.880
feel like they're the
only one in the world that

00:46:08.880 --> 00:46:12.350
feels a certain way, and
clearly had that drive

00:46:12.350 --> 00:46:13.850
to keep you going.

00:46:13.850 --> 00:46:15.330
How do you keep
yourself focused,

00:46:15.330 --> 00:46:17.610
or did you have a
mentor that said

00:46:17.610 --> 00:46:20.254
you know what, just shut
up and keep on doing it.

00:46:20.254 --> 00:46:21.920
Did you have anything
sort of like that?

00:46:21.920 --> 00:46:24.150
MARC ECKO: Yeah, I think
that there's a couple things

00:46:24.150 --> 00:46:27.340
that if you took them
away from me in my life

00:46:27.340 --> 00:46:32.570
that I probably really
be well below average.

00:46:32.570 --> 00:46:37.010
One is having grown up in
Lakewood, New Jersey, which

00:46:37.010 --> 00:46:44.700
was a very diverse place,
and at a time where

00:46:44.700 --> 00:46:46.260
hip hop was emerging.

00:46:46.260 --> 00:46:50.170
So the lens in which
I view the world

00:46:50.170 --> 00:46:53.010
is viewed through
that lens of Lakewood.

00:46:53.010 --> 00:46:55.070
So that gives me a
very different kind

00:46:55.070 --> 00:46:57.530
of cultural view on stuff.

00:46:57.530 --> 00:46:58.130
So that's one.

00:46:58.130 --> 00:47:01.992
Two is I've a twin sister.

00:47:01.992 --> 00:47:03.450
And everything they
say about twins

00:47:03.450 --> 00:47:08.100
is true in terms of best
friend and all that.

00:47:08.100 --> 00:47:10.220
So, if you were to
take Marci, and she's

00:47:10.220 --> 00:47:12.070
as a character
throughout the book,

00:47:12.070 --> 00:47:14.460
I describe her as
my ghost of reason.

00:47:14.460 --> 00:47:18.570
So in a lot of ways, I had
this really interesting yin

00:47:18.570 --> 00:47:26.450
to my yang, who's someone
who's not a visual artist.

00:47:26.450 --> 00:47:29.260
She doesn't need
the fanfare, maybe

00:47:29.260 --> 00:47:31.330
in the way that I'm
more of a narcissistic.

00:47:31.330 --> 00:47:35.270
So I had that throughout
my adolescence

00:47:35.270 --> 00:47:37.720
and then in my career,
and to this day,

00:47:37.720 --> 00:47:40.700
where I still work with
Marci very closely,

00:47:40.700 --> 00:47:44.170
that served me in a way
that I can't contemplate

00:47:44.170 --> 00:47:46.680
life or business without that.

00:47:46.680 --> 00:47:52.149
And my relationship with
mentors had been-- it's

00:47:52.149 --> 00:47:53.690
funny because I
think a lot of people

00:47:53.690 --> 00:47:55.856
prescribe to that idea of
(PATHETIC VOICE) "will you

00:47:55.856 --> 00:47:56.540
be my mentor?"

00:47:56.540 --> 00:47:59.000
And they kind of think of
them like their shrink.

00:47:59.000 --> 00:48:01.250
And they meet with them
once every three weeks

00:48:01.250 --> 00:48:02.290
at the coffee shop.

00:48:02.290 --> 00:48:04.590
And it's kind of
like consistent,

00:48:04.590 --> 00:48:07.490
mostly inconsistent,
but at parties,

00:48:07.490 --> 00:48:08.940
"I want you to meet my mentor."

00:48:08.940 --> 00:48:11.380
I imagine that works.

00:48:11.380 --> 00:48:13.160
I know people that
that's worked for.

00:48:13.160 --> 00:48:16.740
But I found that when there's
a wantedness to learn,

00:48:16.740 --> 00:48:17.830
their learning comes.

00:48:17.830 --> 00:48:19.460
It's there to be gleaned.

00:48:19.460 --> 00:48:21.670
And that you could have
mentor-like relationships

00:48:21.670 --> 00:48:24.420
in the most unsuspecting
places and in a manner that

00:48:24.420 --> 00:48:27.580
doesn't necessarily consume
their schedule on that kind

00:48:27.580 --> 00:48:30.930
of road every two three
weeks kind of a way.

00:48:30.930 --> 00:48:33.920
But alone, yeah, of course.

00:48:33.920 --> 00:48:37.820
I mean, I'm human, right?

00:48:37.820 --> 00:48:40.800
But there's nothing--
I hate to break it

00:48:40.800 --> 00:48:43.530
to myself or to any
entrepreneur, like we're not

00:48:43.530 --> 00:48:45.010
unique in feeling alone.

00:48:45.010 --> 00:48:48.000
It's like welcome to trying
to do shit differently.

00:48:52.702 --> 00:48:55.660
Again, that is, again, a subtext
of the book-- this relationship

00:48:55.660 --> 00:48:57.710
of goal keepers
versus gatekeepers.

00:48:57.710 --> 00:49:00.590
The goal keepers, being
ultimately who you're building,

00:49:00.590 --> 00:49:03.520
trying to execute your vision
for and the gatekeepers,

00:49:03.520 --> 00:49:07.350
being those that guard, kind
of the influencers, the media,

00:49:07.350 --> 00:49:11.212
maybe a buyer, could be a dean
or an academic relationship.

00:49:11.212 --> 00:49:12.670
But those gatekeeper
relationships,

00:49:12.670 --> 00:49:16.750
so much of what we often do,
we want consent from them.

00:49:16.750 --> 00:49:19.810
We want to comply to their
standard and there's a want,

00:49:19.810 --> 00:49:21.780
a cultural wantedness.

00:49:21.780 --> 00:49:24.660
And I would challenge
today, more than ever,

00:49:24.660 --> 00:49:26.710
that you've to be
very cognizant and ask

00:49:26.710 --> 00:49:29.810
yourself are you not
inadvertently building

00:49:29.810 --> 00:49:32.100
your product or service
for the wrong audience,

00:49:32.100 --> 00:49:33.570
versus having a
real intellectually

00:49:33.570 --> 00:49:39.000
honest conversation around
who the goal keeper is,

00:49:39.000 --> 00:49:40.880
who at the consumer
level is really--

00:49:40.880 --> 00:49:44.170
and what do they really
